 of time - to provide new insights into the changing dynamics of lives of women today. In particular, it explores the potential of longitudinal or life course analysis as a powerful tool for appreciating the gender dimension of social life. The contributors view the data from a policy perspective and use comparative analysis from Britain, Germany, the Netherlands, Sweden and Japan to expand our understanding of women's life courses in relation to both men and women and the system of inequality.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2023) 0aLongitudinal methodvCongresses. 0aSocial changevCongresses. 0aSocial policyvCongresses. 0aWomenvCongressesxSocial conditions. 0aWomenxSocial conditionsvCongresses. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / Social Services & Welfare.2bisacsh1 aDale, Angela, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDale, Angela, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDavies, Hugh, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDewilde, Caroline, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDex, Shirley, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aElliott, Jane, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGustafsson, Siv, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJoshi, Heather, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKenjoh, Eiko, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKurz, Karin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRuspini, Elisabetta, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRuspini, Elisabetta, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSmith, Colin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary